+- **Inner-handler naming.** All inner `handler` functions
+  produced by closure factories are uniformly named `handler` at
+  the Python level. This is fine for request parsing (FastAPI
+  reads `inspect.signature(...)`, not `handler.__name__`) but it
+  means Starlette's auto-generated route `name` and the OpenAPI
+  `operationId` collapse to "handler" for every route unless
+  set explicitly. **Mitigation.** Either (a) set
+  `handler.__name__ = "create_task"` (and similar) inside each
+  factory before returning — one assignment per route, mechanical
+  — or (b) pass `name="create_task"` to the `router.<method>(...)`
+  decorator. Wave 1 picks one and applies it uniformly. The repo
+  doesn't appear to consume route names today (no `request.url_for(...)`
+  callers; no OpenAPI-driven client generation), but the OpenAPI
+  spec at `/openapi.json` would otherwise list 43 endpoints all
+  named "handler" which is operator-confusing.
